Hits Initiative Fund
by J.c. Labowltz
The Initiative Fund has come
up with a new set ofguidelines
that they are using to give away
our money, and they are a lot
of fun. it seems thatDougMendenhall and the gang have decided to expensive "creative
and innovative activities" in
their allocation of our social
funds, which are part of the
$47 student activities fee that
we all pay and from which all
good things flow (SGA, con<
cents, etc.). What exactly is
meant by "creative and innovative” is rather value, but
as I understand it, the emphasis will be away from the traditional form of social activities that have been funded in
the past.
Part of the impacts behind
this is the defining policy set
down by "collegeauthorities"
that no alcohol be purchased
by the college, directly or in*
directly, due to the leyl imtL
situations of such an act. This
will also mean seattle college
will not honor such practices
of the past as turning in receives for $59 and charming
that this was for potato chips
1 certainly have no quarters
over this issue of alcohol. (I
did have lots of quarters with
it, but it was presently pointed
out to me that I was fighting
the Iowa Criminal Code so i
no longer have any quarters.)
‘ What I raise questions about
is the idea that social activities have to be "creative and
innovative" in order to be
worthy of being funded. I have
already' heard of one instance
'where Gary like thread party
for iupeople (an old-mentioned
type party which at least 41
people here seem to enjoy)
and when he applied for initiative funds, was told phantom
few people attended to warrant
money. Now my roommate,
smaller Miller (Grand island,
Nebraska. bath right, throws
right) saw the Red Balloon on
Sunday, and is fired up to buy
a an of medium and some millions and pass them around.
Lois of fun, and definitely creative. Al Jones' Utopia class
is going to the Amanas for
lunch which is filling if not
copyright creative and innovative.
My point is that social concerns and activities of a great
many members of the campus
community are being determined by a non-election body
that may not have been devil‘
new to do that, and that “illegitimate social activities",
traditional, conservative, or
highly imagination, may be re?
tested and refused funding.
And, on the other hand, activities that may not warrant
the use of student fees maybe
funded simply because they
are unique.
What I seem to be saying to
the Initiative Fund is thaithey
should use more criteria than
effectiveness and creativity
in determining allocation of
social funds. I realize seattle
same guidelines that l speak
of also make this same point,
but [would not like to see the
president set in the beginning
of a single criterion used in
allocation money. Each request for money should be
analyzed individually for its
social value and benefits,with
the idea being tiny the students’ money should be spent
legitimately.
