SGA Asks references
On JudicialBroposal
by John partner
The Senate has recentlybeen
working on new proposals for
hall judicial councils and for
a campus judicial council.
Their proposals will be combined in a studentrbody references to be distributed
50011.
The present ideas for reorganizing the judicial councils' warnings have been revised from a set of proposals which failed references
passage last semester by a
little less than two percent
(58.7% out of a needed 60%).
Greg Vranicar, Student Coordinator, says that the failure of the proposals was
partly due to the definition
of "open hearings" that was
made, partly due to the large
absorption vote. (conventions
had been defined not to include empty balloon.) These
earlier references proposals, however, have much in
common with the current ones.
Both are shared toward set»
king up hearings for students
who are accused of violation
college or form rules, or
who indicate cases against
forms for violation of their
rights under the Student Bill
of Rights. There are three
basic changes:
first, the definition of "open
hearings" has been changed
from an audience of twenty
people (the first twenty who
show up at the hearing) to
about 72 people (the capacity
of Fine Arts 104). The basic
idea for even this limitation
is to preserve a fairly ordered atmosphere in which
the defendant please his case;
also. peoplewill not developed
to speak at campus~wide her»
they are witnesses.
Second, the Senate has reorganized the composition of
the judicial council to include
three students and two focus‘ ,
ty members, instead of three '\
students and three faculty 5.
members. This change is de- .'
signed to prevent hung votes ,
and also to support a totally»peers concept while uncle»
king faculty viewpoint. ‘
Third, the review power of f;
the campus judicial council
has been more clearly defined.
The judicial council will have '
power to rule on the validity ‘
of any regulation where the '
regulation conﬂacts with one
of three basic documents ‘the SGA constitution, the Student Bill of Rights or any
statute of civil law. This proposed definition would give a
student the power, for example, of appearing to the judicial council if a hall was violation his right, under the ,7
student Bill of Rights, tosieep ’in his room at any time. 9’When the council determines
that a rule has been broken or
that the Bill of Rights is being
increased in some case, the
next step isa recommendation
to the President, on the facts
of the situationandany punishment to be meter out.
